IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
*STATE POLICE IMPAIRED DRIVING REDUCTION EFFORT (S.P.I.D.R.E) TEAM*
MVR Statement: The following incident was captured on in-car camera.
Title: WESLEY "R" 23-196. ID: 23-MSP-012582
Arrested: Wesley, Lashae Andrea.
Certification and training
     -Trained in Field Sobriety Test through Maryland State Police Academy.
     -Trained in Advanced Roadside Impaired Driving Enforcement (A.R.I.D.E)
     -Trained and certified to operate RADAR and LIDAR through the Maryland State Police.
    - Graduated from The Institute of Advanced Law Enforcement Studies Driving Under the Influence Institute-University of Maryland.
     - I have apprehended more than 200 impaired drivers during my tenure with the Maryland State Police to date.
VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1)
          On April 09, 2023, at approximately 0125 hours, I, TFC. I. Riba Tankari # 7058 with Maryland State Police was traveling outer loop I-695 east of Dulaney Valley Road, Baltimore County, Maryland in lane #1 (left lane). My issued patrol vehicle is Maryland State Police marked unit DUI-3. At that time, I observed a silver Honda Accord bearing Maryland temporary registration T1247274 traveling outer loop I-695 in lane #2 (middle lane) unable to stay within a single lane. I observed the Honda had swerved from lane #2 into lane #1 by more than one (1) tire width on two (2) separate occasions. I changed lane into lane #2 and observed the Honda had swerved to the left then to right towards the dotted white line and drove on the dotted line. I followed the vehicle and observed the Honda had swerved from lane #2 into lane #1 by more than one (1) tire on one (1) occasion, applied its brakes before changing lane into lane #3 (right lane). I continued to follow the Honda and observed the vehicle had swerved from lane #3 into lane #2 by more than one tire width then swerved back into lane #3 crossing the dotted white line into the exit lane by more than one (1) one tire width.  
I initiated a traffic stop on the Honda using my emergency equipment. The Honda came to a stop in the area of outer loop I-695 east of Charles Street, Baltimore County, Maryland on the right shoulder.
 PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2)
   While approaching the vehicle, I observed the Honda started moving backwards and almost struck my patrol vehicle.  I approached the Honda on the driver side and made contact with the driver (the sole occupant) of the vehicle. I introduced myself and explained to her the reason for the traffic stop. I requested her driver's license and registration card. I asked the driver where she was coming from, and the driver stated “friend's house.” I asked the driver where she was heading, and she stated “home, Owings mills.” I detected a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from the vehicle. I observed that the driver had watery and glassy eyes. While speaking with the driver I noticed her speech was slow. The driver was identified through her Maryland driver's license as Wesley, Lashae Andrea.
 I returned to my patrol vehicle and notified the barrack who I was out with. I returned to the Honda and I requested Wesley to exit her vehicle and walk to the front of her vehicle and she complied.
I asked Wesley how many alcoholic beverages she had consumed, and she stated she had two (2) glasses of raisin wine. I asked her around what time, and she stated maybe around nine (9) PM. While speaking with Wesley outside her vehicle, I again detected a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from her breath and person. I asked Wesley to submit to Standardized Field Sobriety Tests, and she agreed.
    The evaluation surface was dry, flat, and free of debris. No surface defects were observed. My patrol flashlight, her vehicle headlights, and overhead lamps lit the area. My patrol vehicle's forward emergency lights were deactivated during all three tests. Wesley appeared to be in good physical conditions.
I asked Wesley the following questions:
Medical conditions: No.
Medications: No.
Anything that will prevent you from walking on straight line or standing on one leg: No.
Glasses or contact: No.
PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3)
HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS: (6/6 clues observed).
The Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test was explained and administered per the NHTSA SFST Manual.
- Equal pupil size and equal tracking, no resting nystagmus
- Lack of Smooth Pursuit – Present in both eyes
- Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation – Present in both eyes
- Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees – Present in both eyes
Notes:
* During the HGN test, I continued to detect a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from Wesley's breath.
WALK AND TURN: (4/8 clues observed).
The test was properly explained and demonstrated per the NHTSA SFST Manual.
Wesley stated that she understood the instructions and how the test was to be performed.
Instructional Stage:
Wesley lost her balance to the right on five (5) separate occasions.
Walking Stage (1st Nine):
Missed touching heel to toe by more than two (2) inches on all counts.
Stepped completely offline by one shoe width on all counts.
Turn:
The turn was not completed correctly; instead Wesley moved both feet to turn herself around to left failing to take a series of small steps as instructed and demonstrated.
Walking Stage (2nd Nine):
Missed touching heel to toe by more than two (2) inches on all counts.
Stepped completely offline by one shoe width on all counts.
One Leg Stand Test (2/4 observed)
The test was properly explained and demonstrated per the NHTSA SFST Manual.
Wesley stated that she understood the instructions and how the test was to be performed.
Right foot raised during the test.
Balance and Count Stage:
Seconds 0-10:
Swayed body to the right and left.
Right foot hit the ground one (1) time.
Seconds 11-20:
Swayed body to the right and left.
Seconds 21-30:
Swayed body to the right and left.
Preliminary Breath Test:
    I explained and offered a PBT to Wesley. Wesley elected to consent to the PBT and results were .19 BAC.
ARREST
   Based on the following, I had reason to believe Wesley was driving a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol and was unable to operate a motor vehicle safely:
       -Unable to stay within a single lane/driving patterns. 
       -Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from vehicle.
       -Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from her breath as she conversed with me.
       -Watery and glassy eyes.    
       -Her admissions to consuming alcoholic beverages prior to driving.
       -Observed signs of impairment as she performed the Standardized Field Sobriety Tests.
       - Preliminary Breath Test result of .19 BrAC.
    Wesley was arrested for driving under the influence of alcohol and unable to operate a motor vehicle at 0143 hours and was transported to the Baltimore County Police department Towson Precinct. Upon arrival at the Precinct, Wesley was given a copy of the DR-15 Advice of Rights, and it was read to her from the MVA website in English, and she elected to consent to the Intoximeter EC/IR II test at 0214 hours.
20-MINUTE OBSERVATION PERIOD:
I conducted the 20-minute observation period with Wesley beginning with her arrest. A search revealed that she had nothing in her mouth. She remained in my custody from the time of her arrest. Nothing was introduced to her mouth at any time. The test was conducted by Officer C. Pugh Intox ID #0588 of the Baltimore County Police department on a certified instrument and a result of .17 grams of alcohol per 210 liters of breath was obtained at 0228 hours. Wesley was polite and cooperative during the encounter.
Wesley was given pertinent paperwork and released from the Precinct to her boyfriend pending an appearance in the District Court of Maryland for Baltimore County at a later date.
  All events occurred in Baltimore County, Maryland.
  Case closed by arrest.
